nodes.bodyText:
Rather that passing a List<RoutingFilter> around, requiring all users to handle the iteration, you could just pass a single RoutingFilter which internally handles the iteration.
There are two main ways of achieving this:

The classic way of implementing a type that handles the iteration:

public final class RoutingFilters implements RoutingFilter {

    public RoutingFilters(final List<? extends RoutingFilter> filters) {
         this.filters = ImmutableList.copyOf(requireNonNull(filters));
    }

   public  boolean filter(
      Map<HostInfo, HostStatus> allHostsStatus,
      HostInfo hostInfo,
      String storeName,
      int partition
  ) {
     return filters.stream()
        .allMatch(f -> f.filter(allHostsStatus, hostInfo, storeName, partition));
  }
}

The more functional way of handling filter composition:

@FunctionalInterface
public interface RoutingFilter {

  boolean filter(
      Map<HostInfo, HostStatus> allHostsStatus,
      HostInfo hostInfo,
      String storeName,
      int partition);

  default RoutingFilter and(final RoutingFilter other) {
    Objects.requireNonNull(other);
    return (allHostsStatus, hostInfo, storeName, partition) -> 
        filter(allHostsStatus, hostInfo, storeName, partition) 
            && other.filter(allHostsStatus, hostInfo, storeName, partition);
  }
}
Then you can compose a list of filters into a single filter with:
final Optional<RoutingFilter> reduce = filters.stream()
        .reduce(RoutingFilter::and);
Note, the result is an Optional to handle the case where filters is empty.  If the list is not empty you can just call get().  If the list may be empty then you could use a no-op filter as the default:
final RoutingFilter filter = filters.stream()
        .reduce(RoutingFilter::and)
        .orElse(RoutingFilter.always());
Where always() is:
static RoutingFilter always() {
    return (allHostsStatus, hostInfo, storeName, partition) -> true;
  }

